  <p>For a year now, the Philippines has been engineering friction into the simplest act in online gambling: moving money into an account. First, in August 2025, the Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas ordered e-wallet providers like GCash and Maya to sever their direct links to gaming platforms. Then PAGCOR banned credit cards, to stop people betting with borrowed money, and cryptocurrency, to close the channel unregulated sites used to dodge monitoring. None of this was accidental. The friction <em>is</em> the policy. And it is now meeting the single largest surge in betting demand on the calendar — the World Cup — which is exactly the stress test the design was never able to avoid.</p>

